EDA_Project by Ranjan Kumar

The dataset wineQualityReds contains 1,599 red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent). Our goal here is to identify the chemical properties that influence the quality of red wines.

Univariate Analysis

We can see that all the 11 independent variables are decimals and the dependent variable wine quality is integer.

Looking at the summary of the variables, we can deduce that sulphates, chlorides, residual.sugar and total.sulfur.dioxide have outliers.

It is interesting to know that 95% of the data have rating 5, 6 or 7. We don’t have any missing value and that is great.

I did not create any new variable, because, I felt that all the variables represent a chemical properties/parameter that are difficult to interpret and most likely might not be amenable to any combination. However, I did create a few categorical variables that didn’t prove to be of much use later.

My suscpicion was correct. Out of the eleven plots above; residual.sugar, chlorides, total.sulfur.dioxide and sulphates appear to have long tails. I created a set of new histograms on log10 scale for these variables, and further, I trimmed the top 2.5% of the data. Now, all the variables have a normal or almost normal distribution.

Bivariate Analysis

We can see there is quite significant co-relation among: citric.acid vs fixed.acidity, density vs fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity vs citric.acid and total.sulfur.dioxide vs free.sulfur dioxide.

We can confidently say that the quality of wines on an average increases with fixed.acidity, citric.acid, sulphates and alcohol.

And the quality of wines decraeses with volatile.acidity density and pH.

On a closer analysis, we conclude that residual sugar is inconsiquential to the quality of wines, rather it is almost constant across the spectrum. While, the quality of wine improves as chlorides content decrease and total.sulfur.dioxide content shows an erratic behavior in influenicng the quality of wines. For example, at low total.sulfur.dioxide quality of wine has been observed to be both very good and very bad.

The strongest relationship was obtained for volatile.acidity, citric.acid and alcohol. As, alcohol and citric.acid increase quality of wines improve rapidly, while as the volatile.acidity increases quality of wine deteriorates rapidly.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This plot beautifully shows the efect of citric.acid on the quality of wine. As the concentration of citric.acid increases, it enhances the quality of wine, this is almost a directly proportional relationship.

Plot Two

Description Two

total.sulfur.dioxide presents a very intresting scenario. It is very difficult to determine, how does it affects the quality of wine or is there any effect at all? total.sulfur.dioxide content shows an erratic behavior in influenicng the quality of wines. For example, at low total.sulfur.dioxide concentration quality of wine has been observed to be both very good and very bad.

Plot Three

Description Three

This plot beautifully captures the relationship between most corelated variables and how do they impact the quality. The upper chunk of the cluster of data points have on an average better quality of wine. fixed.acidity in general increases with desnsity, but for a certain density, if the fixed.acidity increases it enhances the quality of the wine.

Reflection

As this is basically a classification problem. We have only the quality as a categorical variable, I tried creating a few factor variables and create new dataframes using dplyr package and tried to observe how a certain variable contribute to quality, when facted by some categorical variable. But, I could not find any observable pattern or any new information that could help understand the data better. Most likely, because, for variables with a long range, particularly a long tail, just three levels like, ‘low’, ‘medium’ and ‘high’, based on 1st and 3rd quartile, is too broad a categorization compromising the benefit of a new variable. Further, due to lack of the domain knowledge, it is difficult to create a regionable no of levels may 6 or 8 or 15, whatever.
